The diseases of globalization
Globalization is being subjected to a harsh test like never before.
Everywhere its tensions are brewing.
The majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling in an economic decline.
North America, Western Europe and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War now threatens Iraq.
For advocates of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
Certain regions, however, have reaped meager benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems in which they are struggling.
The slow growth of Africa, claim American leaders, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of each country's governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to be more performant than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performant than countries that are far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If wealthy countries do not care much about these structural problems, the gaps between the winners and the losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the blame onto the unfortunate countries by claiming that they are somehow culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify turmoil.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move toward a more serious approach to globalization than what wealthy countries, and particularly America, offer.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climatic instability, poor soils, distances from markets, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to raise sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation in a striking way.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing life-saving drugs and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount is just a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases unless it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of blaming the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that are slowing their economic growth and development.
In certain regions like the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity in order to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
Wealthy countries must contribute to funding these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems concern lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all approach of the Washington Consensus is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinkers of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
